

= Rigid Skinning

* Attach rigidly subset of vertices to specific bones, described by its root joint/frame.
** __Vertices are following rigid deformation of their associated frame.__

div::[height:25px;]::

== Deformation formulation

div::[font-size:85%; line-height:1.5em;]
* Consider, at rest pose/initial state
** - A frame \(\mathrm{T}^0\)
** - A vertex \(v^0\) attached to this frame
* After deformation
** - New frame \(\mathrm{T}\)
** - New vertex position \(v\)
::

div::[height:50px;]::

* **Question:** What are the new coordinates \(v\) w/r \(\mathrm{T}\), \(\mathrm{T}^0\), \(v^0\) ?


** \(v^0\) and \(v\) have similar local coordinates w/r to \(\mathrm{T}^0\) and \(\mathrm{T}\) 
** \(\Rightarrow \mathrm{T}^{-1} v = (\mathrm{T}^0)^{-1} v_0\)
** <div class="border">\(\Rightarrow v = \mathrm{T}\;(\mathrm{T}^0)^{-1} v_0 = \mathrm{M}\,v_0\)</div>


